  [2mProject Overview â€“ terminalcp[22m

  terminalcp is a Node.js library and CLI that lets AI agents (or any
  program) control interactive command-line tools just like a human would.
  It provides a "Playwright-for-the-terminal"-style interface that can:

  â€¢ [1mSpawn and manage any CLI process[22m (debuggers, REPLs, build tools, etc.)
  in a pseudo-TTY.
  â€¢ [1mSend keystrokes[22m, special keys, and control sequences to those
  processes.
  â€¢ [1mRead output either as a full rendered screen[22m (for TUIs, debuggers,
  etc.) or as a raw stream (for logs, builds, etc.).
  â€¢ [1mRun multiple sessions simultaneously[22m, with each session persisting
  across client disconnects.
  â€¢ [1mAllow users to attach to AI-spawned sessions[22m (like [38;2;177;185;249mscreen[39m/tmux) to
  watch or intervene.

  [2mKey Features[22m

  â€¢ [1mDebugging[22m: drive LLDB, GDB, pdb, etc., step-by-step.
  â€¢ [1mAI Collaboration[22m: run other AI tools (Claude, Gemini, etc.) as
  subprocesses.
  â€¢ [1mREPL & Shell Interaction[22m: Python, Node, Ruby, database shells, etc.
  â€¢ [1mProcess Management[22m: start, stop, list, and kill sessions via a simple
  JSON-based MCP tool.
  â€¢ [1mTwo output modes[22m:
  - Terminal mode (stdout) â€“ full screen with colors, ideal for TUIs.
  - Stream mode (stream) â€“ raw output, optionally incremental and
  ANSI-stripped.
  â€¢ [1mCLI[22m: terminalcp command provides start, stdin, stdout, stream, list,
  stop, version, etc.
  â€¢ [1mProgrammatic API[22m: TerminalManager class for programmatic control
  (start, sendInput, stdout, stream, stop).

  [2mArchitecture[22m

  1. [1mTerminalManager[22m â€“ core PTY manager (node-pty + xterm.js) handling
  sessions.
  2. [1mTerminalServer[22m â€“ background process listening on a Unix socket,
  persisting sessions.
  3. [1mTerminalClient[22m â€“ communication layer used by both the MCP server and
  CLI.
  4. [1mUser Interfaces[22m â€“ MCP server (exposes terminalcp tool) and CLI
  (stand-alone).

  [2mTypical Use-Cases[22m

  â€¢ [1mAI-driven debugging[22m (LLDB, GDB).
  â€¢ [1mRunning and monitoring builds[22m.
  â€¢ [1mAutomating REPLs or interactive tools[22m.
  â€¢ [1mTesting TUI applications[22m.
  â€¢ [1mAttaching from a real terminal to watch or help AI-spawned processes[22m.

  In short, terminalcp gives AI agents (and developers) a robust,
  programmatic way to run, control, and monitor any interactive terminal
  program, with full PTY emulation and persistent sessions.

  The model switch to GPT OSS 120B was successful, and the complete
  response was captured as requested.
